{"title_page": "David Scearce", "text_new": "'''David Scearce''' is a lawyer and screenwriter.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Law===\nScearce earned a business degree from [[Wilfrid Laurier University]] and a law degree from the [[University of British Columbia]] before joining the [[Department of Justice (Canada)|Justice Department]].<ref name=clerk>{{cite web|url=http://www.clerk.gc.ca/eng/prsns.asp?featureID=0&pageID=196&prsnID=36&thmID=0&dptmntID=0|title=David Scearce|publisher=[[Clerk of the Privy Council (Canada)|Clerk of the Privy Council]]|date=27 September 2012|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\nIn 2000, Scearce decided to write screenplays in his spare time.<ref name=clerk/><ref name=globe>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/david-scearce-white-collar-by-day-red-carpet-by-night/article4188558/|title= David Scearce: White collar by day, red carpet by night |date=4 December 2009|work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |first=Marsha|last=Lederman|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> One of his first attempts was an adaptation of a favourite novel\u2014''A Single Man'' by [[Christopher Isherwood]]. [[Don Bachardy]], Isherwood's surviving partner who managed the rights to the story, approved of the script and it was then picked up by fashion designer and first-time film director [[Tom Ford]]. ''[[A Single Man]]'', starring [[Colin Firth]] and [[Julianne Moore]], premiered at the [[Venice Film Festival]] in September 2009 and was released in December 2009.<ref name=straight>{{cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/movies/vancouverite-david-scearce-succeeds-single-man-screenplay |date=22 December 2009 |work=[[The Georgia Straight]] |title=Vancouverite David Scearce succeeds with A Single Man screenplay |first=Ken |last=Eisner |accessdate=29 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429205201/http://www.straight.com/movies/vancouverite-david-scearce-succeeds-single-man-screenplay |archivedate=29 April 2014 }}</ref>  It and its cast and crew received critical acclaim as well as numerous awards and nominations, including a [[Critics' Choice Movie Award]] nomination for Best Screenplay and an [[Independent Spirit Award]] nomination for [[Independent Spirit Award for Best First Screenplay|Best First Screenplay]].<ref name=globe/>\n\nScearce's second film adaptation, ''[[Measure of a Man (film)|Measure of a Man]]'', a [[coming-of-age story]] based on [[Robert Lipsyte]]'s novel ''[[One Fat Summer]]'', starring [[Blake Cooper]] and [[Donald Sutherland]], was released in 2018.[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2670882/releaseinfo]\n\nIn 2018, Scearce was hired by the Michael Grandage Company to write an adaptation of ''Jack and Lem'', a biography by David Pitts about President [[John F. Kennedy]] and his gay best friend, [[Lem Billings]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/michael-grandage-to-helm-movie-adaptation-of-jack-and-lem|title=Michael Grandage to Helm Movie Adaptation of Jack and Lem|last=Clement|first=Olivia|date=25 July 2018|website=Playbill|language=en|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|3179694}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scearce, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Canadian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Burlington, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Writers from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:LGBT screenwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Canada]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''David Scearce''' is a lawyer and screenwriter.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Law===\nScearce earned a business degree from [[Wilfrid Laurier University]] and a law degree from the [[University of British Columbia]] before joining the [[Department of Justice (Canada)|Justice Department]].<ref name=clerk>{{cite web|url=http://www.clerk.gc.ca/eng/prsns.asp?featureID=0&pageID=196&prsnID=36&thmID=0&dptmntID=0|title=David Scearce|publisher=[[Clerk of the Privy Council (Canada)|Clerk of the Privy Council]]|date=27 September 2012|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\nIn 2000, Scearce decided to write screenplays in his spare time.<ref name=clerk/><ref name=globe>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/david-scearce-white-collar-by-day-red-carpet-by-night/article4188558/|title= David Scearce: White collar by day, red carpet by night |date=4 December 2009|work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |first=Marsha|last=Lederman|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> One of his first attempts was an adaptation of a favourite novel\u2014''A Single Man'' by [[Christopher Isherwood]]. [[Don Bachardy]], Isherwood's surviving partner who managed the rights to the story, approved of the script and it was then picked up by fashion designer and first-time film director [[Tom Ford]]. ''[[A Single Man]]'', starring [[Colin Firth]] and [[Julianne Moore]], premiered at the [[Venice Film Festival]] in September 2009 and was released in December 2009.<ref name=straight>{{cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/movies/vancouverite-david-scearce-succeeds-single-man-screenplay |date=22 December 2009 |work=[[The Georgia Straight]] |title=Vancouverite David Scearce succeeds with A Single Man screenplay |first=Ken |last=Eisner |accessdate=29 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429205201/http://www.straight.com/movies/vancouverite-david-scearce-succeeds-single-man-screenplay |archivedate=29 April 2014 }}</ref>  It and its cast and crew received critical acclaim as well as numerous awards and nominations, including a [[Critics' Choice Movie Award]] nomination for Best Screenplay and an [[Independent Spirit Award]] nomination for [[Independent Spirit Award for Best First Screenplay|Best First Screenplay]].<ref name=globe/>\n\nScearce's second film adaptation, ''[[Measure of a Man (film)|Measure of a Man]]'', a [[coming-of-age story]] based on [[Robert Lipsyte]]'s novel ''[[One Fat Summer]]'', starring [[Blake Cooper]] and [[Donald Sutherland]], was released in 2018.[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2670882/releaseinfo]\n\nIn 2018, Scearce was hired by the Michael Grandage Company to write an adaptation of ''Jack and Lem'', a biography by David Pitts about President [[John F. Kennedy]] and his gay best friend, [[Lem Billings]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/michael-grandage-to-helm-movie-adaptation-of-jack-and-lem|title=Michael Grandage to Helm Movie Adaptation of Jack and Lem|last=Clement|first=Olivia|date=25 July 2018|website=Playbill|language=en|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|3179694}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scearce, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Canadian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Burlington, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Writers from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:LGBT screenwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Canada]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Scearce"}
